Is it possible to regulate systemic risks?
MILAN – Over the past two years, the global economy has been hit hard by financial instability and sudden changes in market dynamics.
Other events of this kind are likely, because following the crisis, the global economy is imbalanced in many respects, particularly from the perspective of sovereign debt and the structure of global demand.
Systemic risks are the cause of most crises and present a challenge for several reasons.
First of all, they are not easy to detect safely and even more difficult to prove.
Next, predicting the exact moment of the breaking point (when bubbles burst, when markets are paralyzed, and when credit is no longer available) is, and will likely remain, beyond our analytical capabilities.
Finally, crises are strongly nonlinear events that occur without prior warning signs.
Periodic manifestations of instability impose a high social cost on those least responsible for them.
If this pattern were to repeat, it could undermine confidence in financial markets and regulatory authorities, a loss of confidence that could lead to excessive regulations, state intervention, and a retreat from globalization.
But the problem is even more serious.
The financial and economic crisis is turning into a sovereign debt crisis in advanced countries.
Economic and financial imbalances can lead to a dangerous fiscal imbalance, characterized by a deterioration of tax revenues and an increase in bailout expenditures.
The International Monetary Fund estimates that up to 75 percent of the "fiscal packages" of advanced economies include non-discretionary countercyclical measures.
Undetected imbalances and systemic risks make fiscal policies that seem prudent in fact not prudent.
For example, Spain did not have a fiscal deficit at the beginning of the crisis.
But his income and expenses were largely determined by a housing bubble linked to very high levels of debt.
An extreme fiscal imbalance can also lead to a "growth trap" in which fiscal consolidation has such a negative effect on growth that it cancels itself out.
Greece is undoubtedly a typical example.
In the end, the only way out is to reset the value of liabilities through restructuring or inflation.
If systemic risks can cause this kind of sequential cascading imbalance, sovereign states must be attentive to the danger, capable of identifying the emergence of a systemic risk and quickly taking corrective measures.
New detailed legislative frameworks, emphasizing capital requirements and leverage, transparency, ratings and other sources of information, incentives, conflicts of interest and limits on the size of financial institutions, consumer protection, and resolution mechanisms are about to be adopted.
The hope is that these reforms will reduce the probability and severity of systemic risks.
But this will in no way resolve the issue of global imbalances and other factors contributing to and signaling instability.
In addition to and as a complement to new legislative frameworks, a comprehensive system for monitoring systemic risks is necessary.
However, some prominent politicians and analysts believe that such a system, aimed at identifying and containing systemic risks, is futile.
Incomplete models of risk dynamics and a complex, ever-evolving global financial system make risk detection, in their view, either impossible or so prone to error that such an effort would be unproductive.
Asset bubbles are almost impossible to identify without error.
If the skeptics are right, we must then accept that we will periodically find ourselves in a situation of financial and fiscal instability without being able to predict it in advance.
We should then also accept a much more prudent fiscal policy than the one we considered necessary just three years ago.
In the field of statistics and decision-making under uncertainty, errors are inevitable.
There are two types of errors: one is rejecting a true proposition, and the other is accepting a false proposition.
Let's call them RQV (rejected when true) and AQF (accepted when false).
The question can be phrased as follows: in the context of detecting and responding to systemic risks, which of these two types of errors has the highest probable cost?
The opponents of cautious systemic risk monitoring have two different positions.
One of them is that the AQF error will not occur, because there are no reliable signs indicating a potentially increasing instability.
Looking for such a sign is a waste of time.
The instability occurs instantaneously.
But this position seems fallacious.
For example, during the 2008 crisis, some analysts issued warnings and some investors took note of them.
However, it must be acknowledged that these warnings were perhaps not sufficient to be irrefutable, and they certainly did not foresee the breaking point.
They were nevertheless undeniably signs.
The second position is that there are indeed signs, but they are so unreliable that taking measures would do more harm than good.
This viewpoint implies that AQF has a probably higher cost than RQV, because there are many false positives and/or the remedy is worse than the problem.
There is no doubt that there are costs associated with AQF errors.
But RQV is also costly, as we have seen, so the aggregate negative effect of reacting to false positives (FP) must be significant to be convincing.
As for me, I am not convinced.
There may be a deeper trend at play.
Whether in business or investments, decisions are constantly made under conditions of uncertainty, and errors are frequent.
On the contrary, the default position of decision-makers in advanced countries seems to be that proactive and preemptive measures require a high level of certainty, linked to the deeply rooted belief that financial markets are stable and self-regulating.
If one considers that market instability is rare, it is then reasonable to refuse to act unless there are good reasons to do so.
But in light of past experiences, the idea that the global financial system is only exceptionally unstable or on a downward spiral is at the very least questionable.
Based on new theories and experiences, we might eventually conclude that political responses to systemic risks are impossible to develop and that the cost of AQF errors is higher than the cost of RQV errors.
But we should at least try this approach, and to do so, assign responsibilities to a new institution or an existing one that has access to relevant information, possesses advanced analytical skills at both the financial and macroeconomic levels, and is relatively free from conflicts of interest.
His analysis should be made public and could thereby influence the perception of systemic risks and market behavior, thereby increasing the capacity of the financial system to self-regulate.
